{
  "doc_id": "864",
  "text": "There are several identified collections of sorghum genetic resources (for example core-collections [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , US converted tropical and breeding lines described in [CITATION_3] , US sweet sorghum collection [CITATION_4] , mutant populations [CITATION_5] , Japanese collection [CITATION_6] , as well as accessions available at ICRISAT). Sorghum's center of diversity lies in the northeastern quadrant of Africa and it is thought sorghum was domesticated there over 5,000 years before present [CITATION_7] . Based on spikelet and grain morphology, Harlan and de Wet [CITATION_8] developed a simplified classification of traditional sorghum cultivars into five basic races: Bicolor (B), Caudatum (C), Durra (D), Guinea (G) and Kafir (K), and ten intermediate races (in all pair-wise combinations of basic races).",
